Title: Phase diagram of carbon at high pressures and temperatures  
Author: Matthew P. Grumbach and Richard M. Martin 
Note: Typeset using REVT  
Date: (November 8, 1996)  
Address: Urbana, IL 61801  
Affiliation: Department of Physics and Materials Research Laboratory, University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign,  E X  
Abstract: We have made a systematic study of solid and liquid phases of carbon over a wide range of pressures and temperatures using first principles molecular dynamics. Our simulations elucidate three aspects of the phase diagram: 1) the melting of the simple cubic phase at 35-40 Mbar; 2) structural changes in the liquid in the range of 4-10 Mbar; and 3) the melting of the BC-8 phase at ~22 Mbar. We combine the results of these three investigations to construct a proposed phase diagram for carbon. In particular, we find that above ~6 Mbar the liquid state has ~6-fold coordination, and, consequently, that the melting temperatures of the solids in this pressure range tend to decrease with increasing pressure. 
